metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #138
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of Specterüëªpixel‚¨õlatte‚òï, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agents‚Äîthe small moving circles‚Äîthat get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.

metadata.name: Interlaced #215
metadata.description:
From African tribal clothes to Islamic mosaics every civilization throughout history has produced delicate patterns to share the essence of their culture. These artifacts have changed our understanding of how art, like societies form through bonds, the very fabric of things that have become symbols for cycles, paths and relationships.

Interlaced explores these unique motifs using emergent algorithms to produce colorful continuous patterns. The project uses a dynamic engine that traverses triangular meshes placing diverse tile configurations. By combining art with technology, the project aims to tell a new story of making digital connections between geography, culture and time.

Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save in high-resolution.

metadata.name: Mythic Latent Glitches  #123
metadata.description:
What is even real and what is artificial?

In the contemporary light, the division between real and artificial loses weight as the concepts become more and more intertwined. In this work, the artist combines the human and generative inputs, in a counterintuitive manner, by allowing AI to design the organic elements and using the human hand to incorporate artificial glitches. What seemingly emerges as natural forms, was imagined solely by GAN, seeing the world through the limited examples through the photographer‚Äôs lenses. Artist‚Äôs role is also reversed, as their goal is to design the visual destruction process of the organic forms. Glitch is a malfunction of perception, it symbolizes the confusion caused by not being able to comprehend. 

The human fascination with metaphysical forces spans many centuries. While Pagan mythology created gods living in deep forests and under-explored territories, nowadays we approach technology with somewhat similar awe, fascination, and fear. 

The project has been developed in multiple stages. It started with an inspiration by the Lithuanian landscape and research of the ancient myths and legends. The photography aimed at capturing the mysterious, spanning months and years of different experiences. A custom pre-trained artist‚Äôs GAN model was then trained on a collection of several hundred photographs in high resolution. Selected outputs were curated by artist and included as a starting canvas for the next stage. Then, a set of stochastic manipulations were programmed to create alternative narratives through the visual destruction. Fog turns into smoke into burning radioactive forest in an unpredictable manner, guided by the random variables, their boundaries crafted by artist.  

Read more on the project website:
ivonatau.com/mythic-latent-glitches

- Use the "A" key to animate (if "Animated" feature is present).
- Press any key to stop the animation.
- Use the "S" key to export an image.

metadata.name: Balancium #134
metadata.description:
"Balancium" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

In the fall of 1931, in Alexander Calder's studio, Marcel Duchamp coined the term 'mobile' for his kinetic sculptures. Later, Calder wrote: "This, in French, means not only 'movable'‚Äî but also a 'motive', 'a reason for an act' so I found it a very good word."
 
Around the same year, Bruno Munari started making colorful and whimsical mobiles. He called them "useless machines", existing without any purpose and inviting viewers to just look. Elements are connected with nearly invisible threads or wires, allowing the artist to create the illusion of shapes floating in the air.

Balancium is both a virtual mobile and a useless object. Generated by the code, it undergoes a continual transformation. The movement of the air, or invisible fluid, becomes an integral part of the design and amplifies serenity. 
 
There is a keyboard key that unlocks more variations.

metadata.name: Calmer waters #24
metadata.description:
I long for calmer waters. This piece is about that. It's a counterpoint. It reflects some of my best memories of the sea: the warm salty air on my face, interspersed with a cool breeze, leaving my lips salty tasting. The gentle rushing of the water. 

The sea with its vast panorama's can make you feel insignificant in the grand scheme of things. But this piece is about hope.

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #216
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Art blocks #1
metadata.description:
This is an exploration the possibility of repeatable patterns. There are 6 patterns in total with 120 color palettes. The work is responsive to the height of the viewport, thus a same piece of art may render different result because of different device‚Äôs resolutions. This gives the fun of having different perspectives from different views. Also, the art the BEST IN FULL SCREEN. 

Rarity:
Pattern 0 - 20%
Pattern 1 -5%
Pattern 2 - 15%
Pattern 3 - 30%
Pattern 4 - 15%
Pattern 5 - 20%

- Press "p" to pause/unpause the animation
- Press "s" to save the image

NOTE: there‚Äôs a noise generation, which costs tons of computing power, at the end of the animation. If you find out your browse freezes, or a popup tells you that the page is dead, just BE PATIENT AND WAIT about 0.5-1 minutes for the result :)

metadata.name: Sketch A #25
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch A starts very simple. It's the basic grid framework I intend to use for the series. It's just a simple grid with one colored square (usually). Colors are borrowed from Echos/Orbits. Grid size, padding, and line thickness vary.
